<HEADLINE>
<P>
POLICE FOUND NO BASIS FOR CHARGES AGAINST DR. HERDEG 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Dr. Brian Herdeg has been an outstanding resident of the West Valley for 37 
years, and during those years, by his active involvement in civic affairs, he 
has contributed a great deal to this community. It is very unfortunate that you 
choose to sensationalize allegations by an unnamed woman that besmirch the 
doctor's fine reputation.The identity of "S.M." is protected, while her charges 
against Dr. Herdeg are reported in graphic detail. 
</P>
<P>
 Your reporter may think that he reported the story objectively because he did 
interview the doctor and quote him, but the reporter failed to include this 
pertinent information: The Los Angeles Police Department and district 
attorney's office had investigated the case more than a year ago and determined 
there was not a sound basis for filing charges. Furthermore, criticism by the 
California Legislature of the state medical board's handling of some past 
complaints against physicians has caused that body to press for judicial 
involvement in cases that were previously handled internally. 
</P>
<P>
 I know I speak for many, many people -- patients, friends and acquaintances -- 
when I express my own feelings of sorrow that Dr. Herdeg and his family must 
endure the pain of this type of publicity. There will be hearings and 
testimony, and there will ultimately be an outcome. I hope The Times will give 
as much space and prominence to an article fully clearing the doctor's name at 
that time. 
</P>
<P>
 EVELYN P. BORDEN 
</P>
<P>
 Woodland Hills 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Letter to the Editor 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA110894-0088 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 096451 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
