<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE WEEK AHEAD: BERLIN; A WREATH AT THE WALL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Commemorating the fifth anniversary of the fall of the Berlin Wall, 140 
Americans will lay a wreath Wednesday to honor Germans shot while trying to 
cross the old divide, then hold a candlelight march from the eastern half of 
the city to the west. 
</P>
<P>
 The event, organized by the Citizen Ambassador Program of People to People 
International, from Spokane, Wash., will follow a day of workshops on efforts 
to unite the people of eastern and western Germany. 
</P>
<P>
 The American organization has invited Germans to participate and has the 
blessing of Berlin City Hall, says program spokeswoman Barbara Schulte. But she 
added: "We wish thousands of Germans would participate, but I don't think so. 
Berliners don't like a memorial to that date. The wall is still in their 
heads." 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA110894-0112 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 096475 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</SOURCE>
<DATE>
<P>
November 8, 1994, Tuesday, Home Edition 
</P>
