<HEADLINE>
<P>
WEEKEND BOX OFFICE; 'STARGATE' A BACK-TO-BACK CHAMP 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ROBERT W. WELKOS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 MGM's surprise autumn hit "Stargate" won the box-office sweepstakes for the 
second weekend in a row, capitalizing on good word-of-mouth, a PG-13 rating 
that pulled in youngsters and a strong allegiance among science-fiction fans 
who communicate their support over the Internet global computer network. Laden 
with special effects, "Stargate" pulled in $12.4 million from Friday through 
Sunday.The film also capitalized on the appeal of Kurt Russell, who has built a 
following among the sci-fi community since his 1981 film "Escape From New 
York," and the presence of James Spader, playing a role unlike those he has 
played in the past. 
</P>
<P>
 TriStar's "Mary Shelley's Frankenstein," starring Kenneth Branagh and Robert 
De Niro, had to overcome mixed reviews and an R-rating to take in $11.2 million 
and wind up in second place. Far behind in third place was "The War," starring 
Elijah Wood and Kevin Costner, which grossed $5.2 million. Meanwhile, Paramount 
Pictures' remarkable film, "Forrest Gump," remained in the top 10 for the 18th 
week, coming in ninth place with about $2 million for the weekend. Weekend Box 
